<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-27T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="93" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d93">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9315 Manchuria/200: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-27T21:00:00+03:00">December 27,
                                1939—9 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received December 27—8:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1141. My 915, November 20, 10 a.m. I understand that the Soviet-Japanese
                        Mixed Commission which has been sitting at Chita for the purpose of
                        establishing a definite boundary between Mongolia and Manchuria has reached
                        an agreement on this question and that the commission will move to Harbin on
                        January 7 and proceed to the physical demarcation of the frontier.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>